WEEK 4: Foundations of Test Cases & Test Data Preparation
1ï¸âƒ£ What is a Test Case?
A Test Case is a set of steps written to verify whether a specific feature of the software is working as expected.

ğŸ§  Simple definition (exam ready):
A test case is a document that describes the steps, input, and expected result to test a software feature.

2ï¸âƒ£ Why Test Cases are IMPORTANT?

âœ… Ensures proper coverage
âœ… Avoids missing scenarios
âœ… Helps new testers understand the system
âœ… Useful for regression testing
âœ… Acts as documentation

ğŸ“Œ Industry fact:
Companies do not test without test cases (except exploratory testing).

3ï¸âƒ£ Standard Test Case Format

Most companies follow something close to this:
Field                	Description
Test Case ID	        Unique identifier
Test Scenario	        What to test
Preconditions	        Setup before testing
Test Steps	          Step-by-step actions
Test Data	            Input values
Expected Result	      What should happen
Actual Result	        What actually happened
Status	              Pass / Fail
Remarks              	Additional notes

4ï¸âƒ£ Example: Login Page Test Case


Test Case ID: TC_LOGIN_01
Scenario: Verify login with valid credentials

Preconditions:
User must be registered

Steps:
Open login page
Enter valid username
Enter valid password
Click Login

Test Data:
Username: test@gmail.com
Password: Test@123

Expected Result:
User should be redirected to dashboard
Status: Pass

5ï¸âƒ£ What is a Test Suite?
A Test Suite is a collection of related test cases.

ğŸ“Œ Example:
Login Test Suite contains:
Valid login test
Invalid login test
Blank fields test
Forgot password test

ğŸ§  One-liner:
Test suite groups similar test cases together.

6ï¸âƒ£ Executing Test Cases
Test Execution means:
Running test cases and comparing expected vs actual results.

Steps:
Prepare test environment
Execute test cases
Note actual results
Mark Pass/Fail
Report defects if any

ğŸ“Œ Real Life:
If expected â‰  actual â†’ BUG FOUND

7ï¸âƒ£ Recording Test Results

After execution, results are recorded as:
Pass â€“ Feature works as expected
Fail â€“ Mismatch found
Blocked â€“ Cannot test due to dependency
Not Executed â€“ Test not run yet

ğŸ§  Interview Tip:
Blocked â‰  Failed

8ï¸âƒ£ Defect (Bug) Tracking â€“ Intro
A Defect/Bug is:
A deviation between expected and actual result.

When do we log a bug?
Test case fails
Application crashes
Incorrect behavior observed

ğŸ“Œ Example:
Password field accepts only 6 chars but requirement says 8.

9ï¸âƒ£ Entry Criteria & Exit Criteria (VERY IMPORTANT)
ğŸ”¹ Entry Criteria
Conditions that must be met before testing starts.

Examples:
Requirements approved
Test cases ready
Test environment available

ğŸ”¹ Exit Criteria
Conditions to stop testing.
Examples:
All test cases executed
Critical bugs fixed
Test coverage achieved

ğŸ§  Easy difference:
Entry â†’ When to START
Exit â†’ When to STOP

